---
/**
 * production-ai-architecture/0001 · Figure 1 — the hero: "the whole review in one
 * picture" (an AI feature is a normal service calling a remote model dependency).
 *
 * Copied VERBATIM from
 * docs/production-ai-architecture/lessons/0001-reviewing-ai-like-a-distributed-system.html
 * (figure + svg + figcaption incl. the footnote <sup>). Lives as an .astro
 * component, NOT inline in the MDX, because MDX's JSX parser is unreliable with
 * raw inline SVG that uses kebab-case attributes (text-anchor, font-size,
 * stroke-width, marker-end, …). The marker ids (#arw) it references are defined
 * once by Defs.astro, rendered before this figure. The #s1 footnote anchors
 * (r1, r1b) are kept as-is to match the source DOM.
 */
---

<figure>
    <svg
        viewBox="0 0 640 320"
        role="img"
        aria-label="An AI feature is a normal service calling a remote model dependency; the same review lenses apply, with non-determinism added as the one new variable bending each lens."
    >
        <!-- the service spine -->
        <rect
            x="36"
            y="150"
            width="120"
            height="46"
            rx="8"
            fill="#eef2f7"
            stroke="#1f3a5a"
            stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
        <text x="96" y="171" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >Your service</text
        >
        <text x="96" y="186" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f">request in</text>
        <rect
            x="260"
            y="150"
            width="120"
            height="46"
            rx="8"
            fill="#f1eef2"
            stroke="#b5179e"
            stroke-width="2"></rect>
        <text x="320" y="171" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#b5179e"
            >Model call</text
        >
        <text x="320" y="186" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f"
            >remote · rate-limited</text
        >
        <rect
            x="484"
            y="150"
            width="120"
            height="46"
            rx="8"
            fill="#eef2f7"
            stroke="#1f3a5a"
            stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
        <text x="544" y="171" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >Answer out</text
        >
        <text x="544" y="186" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f">maybe wrong</text>
        <line x1="156" y1="173" x2="256" y2="173" stroke="#6b675f" marker-end="url(#arw)"></line>
        <line x1="380" y1="173" x2="480" y2="173" stroke="#6b675f" marker-end="url(#arw)"></line>

        <!-- the lenses -->
        <rect
            x="36"
            y="40"
            width="172"
            height="60"
            rx="10"
            fill="#eef2f7"
            stroke="#1f3a5a"
            stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
        <text x="122" y="60" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="#1f3a5a"
            >Reliability</text
        >
        <text x="122" y="78" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#6b675f"
            >correct-enough,</text
        >
        <text x="122" y="92" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#6b675f">not just up</text>
        <rect
            x="234"
            y="40"
            width="172"
            height="60"
            rx="10"
            fill="#eef2f7"
            stroke="#1f3a5a"
            stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
        <text x="320" y="60" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="#1f3a5a"
            >Scalability</text
        >
        <text x="320" y="78" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#6b675f"
            >tokens/sec vs a</text
        >
        <text x="320" y="92" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#6b675f"
            >provider limit</text
        >
        <rect
            x="432"
            y="40"
            width="172"
            height="60"
            rx="10"
            fill="#eef2f7"
            stroke="#1f3a5a"
            stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
        <text x="518" y="60" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="#1f3a5a"
            >Observability</text
        >
        <text x="518" y="78" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#6b675f"
            >+ a quality axis:</text
        >
        <text x="518" y="92" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#6b675f">was it right?</text
        >

        <line
            x1="122"
            y1="100"
            x2="100"
            y2="148"
            stroke="#1f3a5a"
            stroke-dasharray="3 3"
            marker-end="url(#arw)"></line>
        <line
            x1="320"
            y1="100"
            x2="320"
            y2="148"
            stroke="#1f3a5a"
            stroke-dasharray="3 3"
            marker-end="url(#arw)"></line>
        <line
            x1="518"
            y1="100"
            x2="540"
            y2="148"
            stroke="#1f3a5a"
            stroke-dasharray="3 3"
            marker-end="url(#arw)"></line>

        <!-- the one new variable -->
        <rect
            x="200"
            y="116"
            width="240"
            height="22"
            rx="11"
            fill="#fbecec"
            stroke="#9a2417"
            stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
        <text x="320" y="131" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" font-weight="700" fill="#9a2417"
            >+ ONE new variable: non-determinism</text
        >

        <text x="320" y="234" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" font-style="italic" fill="#b5179e"
            >Same skeleton as any service you've shipped. The model is just a flaky, remote,
            non-deterministic dependency.</text
        >
        <text x="320" y="258" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" fill="#6b675f"
            >Reliability theory isn't reinvented — it's inherited from SRE and distributed systems
            and bent by three deltas.</text
        >
        <text x="320" y="294" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >The deltas: correctness is reliability · tokens are capacity · quality is a monitored
            signal.</text
        >
    </svg>
    <figcaption>
        The whole review in one picture. You already know how to review a service that depends on a
        remote, rate-limited, occasionally-down API. AI adds exactly one thing — the dependency can
        be <em>wrong</em>, not just down — and that single fact bends reliability, scalability, and
        observability.<sup><a href="#s1" id="r1b">1</a></sup>
    </figcaption>
</figure>
